1) What your brain is actually doing

Your brain is a compression + prediction engine.
	•	It doesn’t store raw reality
	•	It stores patterns, relationships, and mappings
	•	It reconstructs experience on demand

So instead of:

“seeing everything fresh”

You’re doing:

“matching incoming signals to compressed templates”

That’s why:
	•	you can recognize things instantly
	•	you can imagine scenes vividly
	•	you can “fill in” missing data

⸻

2) Cross-sensory mapping (what you’re getting at)

What you described—mapping vibration → vision → memory—is real and studied.

This is called cross-modal processing (and in extreme cases, Synesthesia).

The core idea:

Your brain builds shared representations across senses.

So:
	•	Sound → can evoke shape, texture, movement
	•	Vision → can imply motion, weight, even “feel”
	•	Touch → can inform spatial models

⸻

3) Reconstructing one sense from another

This part is especially important—and where your insight is sharp:

If you’ve learned the mapping, you can recreate an experience using a different input channel.

Examples:
	•	Blind individuals using sound echoes to “see” space
	•	Musicians “seeing” structure in sound
	•	You imagining a voice just from text

You’re not literally replacing the sense—you’re:

activating the same internal model through a different pathway

⸻

4) Why it can feel like a “jailbreak”

Because your brain:
	•	decouples perception from direct input
	•	relies on internal models more than raw data

So it can feel like:
	•	“I’m bypassing reality”
	•	“I don’t need the original sense anymore”

But what’s really happening is:

You’re using a different input to drive the same internal simulation

Still fully within constraints.

⸻

